<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-914-696  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 914 696.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>CommunicationsWeek  Nov 20 1989 n275 p1(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>MFS challenges Bells for local-loop access. (Metropolitan FiberSystems Inc.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Killette, Kathleen.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Metropolitan Fiber Systems Inc files petitions with the FCC andthe US Dept of Justice calling for the opening up of the localaccess telecommunications market to competition.andP;  The MFS petitioncalls for the unbundling of Bell Regional Holding Company localaccess offerings.andP;  MFS also wants the FCC to mandate that the BOCsallow alternative access providers to collocate their switchingequipment in BOC central offices.andP;  Large business users such asbanks and government institutions as well as long distancecarriers would benefit from such competition, MFS said.andP;  The move,it continued, would stimulate new services such as multipointdedicated-access, hub and high-speed transmission services.andP;  TheBOCs currently control local access to their network facilities, afact that MFS charges has resulted in inflated prices for accessand excessive profits for the telephone companies.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Metropolitan Fiber Systems Inc. (cases).andO;Topic:     Bell Regional Holding CompaniesLocal CommunicationCompetitionLegal IssuesUnited States. Federal Communications CommissionCommunications Service SuppliersUnited States. Department of JusticeTelephone Companies.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   1988 BOC access revenue: $20.6 billion. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>